<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="220" pageId="11" pageNumber="218" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1074,1366,1660]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1074,1569,1656]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="220" pageId="11" pageNumber="218">
REMARKS: The female examined belongs to the 
<emphasis box="[746,835,1573,1596]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="218">savignyi</emphasis>
-group on the basis of genital morphology. It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[603,708,1605,1628]" class="Arachnida" family="Hersiliidae" genus="Hersilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striata">
<emphasis box="[603,708,1605,1628]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="218">H. striata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the insemination ducts curving downwards and then ascending laterad, the rectangular bulbose sacs of the spermathecae with pilose apices and the ovoid receptacula separated from one other. However, the female examined slightly differ in the shape of the apices on the bulbose sacs which are round and clearly separate from the remaining membranous parts by thickenings (
<figureCitation box="[274,399,1634,1657]" captionStart-0="FIGS 25-26" captionStart-1="FIGS 27-31" captionStartId-0="12.[545,587,630,651]" captionStartId-1="12.[550,592,1407,1428]" captionTargetBox-0="[136,1058,227,600]" captionTargetBox-1="[136,1058,729,1365]" captionTargetId-0="figure@12.[136,1058,226,600]" captionTargetId-1="figure@12.[136,1058,729,1366]" captionTargetPageId-0="12" captionTargetPageId-1="12" captionText-0="FIGS 25-26 Hersilia cf. striata. (25) Epigyne, ventral view. (26) Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 1.0 mm." captionText-1="FIGS 27-31 Hersilia asiatica (27), H. sundaica (28, 31), H. cf. striata (29), H. serrata sp. n., paratype (30). (27-28) Vulva, dorsal view. (29-30) Right half of vulva, dorsal view. (31) Seminal receptacle." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/305456/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/305460/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="219">Figs 26, 29</figureCitation>
). The separation is indistinct and the thickening of the apices is not prominent in females of 
<taxonomicName box="[519,628,1569,1592]" class="Arachnida" family="Hersiliidae" genus="Hersilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="13" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striata">
<emphasis box="[519,628,1569,1592]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="220">H. striata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, the female examined from Thailand cannot be identified with certainty pending an examination of the Chinese types.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
